'It is a huge decision and not one I've taken lightly obviously because I could have played my last game,' he added.

The
 Sussex wicketkeeper has come under fire during an England slump which 
extended to 10 Tests without a win on Monday as India triumphed by 95 
runs at Lord's, with Prior only managing 12 runs in the second innings 
as Ishant Sharma tore through England's middle order.

Prior says he 
has made the decision for the good of the team and has wished whoever 
comes in to replace him - likely to be Lancashire's Jos Buttler - the 
best of luck.

'I've made my decision for the good of the team and 
whoever comes in I genuinely wish them the best of luck and hope they go
 well and perform and help the team win. That is all I want,' he said.

'If
 that happens and I don't play again, then that was my lot. I'll be 
disappointed because there are a few things that I wanted to achieve and
 thought I would, but I can also look back and know I did some pretty 
good things.'

